ter, on the Western Reserve, he was commissioned major-general of the Ohio militia. The frontier soldier had become the frontier's general."},{"number":2,"category":"legacy","header":"The house he built became Harriet Beecher Stowe's","body":"The frame house Wadsworth raised at Canfield in 1803 was the first in the township. Generations later it passed into the hands of the Beecher family. The pioneer's homestead outlived the pioneer by a long way."},{"number":3,"category":"business","header":"An original signer of the Connecticut Land Company","body":"In September 1795 Wadsworth was among the signers of the contract that opened the Western Reserve to settlement. He spent the summer of 1799 scouting Canfield and the surrounding towns. By 1802 he had moved his whole family west by horse and ox team."},{"number":4,"category":"military","header":"He held the frontier after Hull's surrender","body":"When war was declared in 1812 and General Hull surrendered Detroit, Wadsworth was called into active service as a major-general. He threw his full energy into defending the exposed Ohio frontier. Contemporaries credited him with a real service to the country."},{"number":5,"category":"legacy","header":"A whole Ohio city now bears his name","body":"Wadsworth, Ohio, in Medina County, is named for the general. He had once owned a significant portion of the land on which the city grew. His name outlasted his fortune, which the Revolution had consumed entirely."}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"H00757","display_label":"Served under Tallmadge in Sheldon's Horse — both ended up in the Western Reserve","link_text":"Maj. Benjamin Tallmadge Jr."},{"type":"birthplace_connection","related_id":"X02034","display_label":"Harriet Beecher Stowe was born in 1811 in the Litchfield house Wadsworth built, after it passed to her father Rev. Lyman Beecher.","link_text":"Harriet Beecher Stowe"},{"type":"civic_connection","related_id":"X03131","display_label":"largest buyer of that township; Canfield, Ohio named for him"}],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST0045","relationship":"member","years":"1795-1802","institution_blurb":"Member of the Connecticut Land Company; agent for Canfield Township 1799-1802."},{"institution_id":"INST035"}],"landmarks":[{"landmark_id":"LM033","landmark_blurb":"He built it in 1774; sold to Lyman Beecher in 1810 — Harriet Beecher Stowe was born there in 1811."},{"landmark_id":"LM131","landmark_blurb":"The 1799 Litchfield house he built, now the Oliver Wolcott Library."}],"military_service":[{"war":"American Revolutionary War","side":"American","rank":"Captain","unit":"Sheldon's Horse — 2nd Continental Light Dragoons","notes":"Served directly under Maj. Benjamin Tallmadge. Co-founded Sheldon's Horse. Served Long Island, Monmouth, Yorktown. Was at West Point when Major André was taken prisoner, 1780.","war_id":"WAR004"},{"war":"War of 1812","side":"American","rank":"Major General","unit":"4th Division, Ohio State Militia","notes":"Commanded Elisha Whittlesey (X01997) as aide. Organized 3,000-man militia; built forts and roads across NE Ohio. Commanded at Battle of the Peninsula, Sep 10, 1812. Resigned Feb 1814 due to age/health. Personal debt of $26,551 supplying troops — Congress discharged 1825.","war_id":"WAR009"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Gen. Elijah Wadsworth","first_name":"Elijah","last_name":"Wadsworth","title":"General","married_names":[],"bio_blurb":"Revolutionary officer; Ohio militia general"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"career":[{"role":"Captain","organization":"Continental Army","end_year":1783,"notes":"Served under Benjamin Tallmadge"},{"role":"Major-General","organization":"Ohio Militia (4th Division)","start_year":1804,"notes":"Recalled to active service in the War of 1812"},{"role":"Postmaster / Sheriff","organization":"Canfield, Trumbull County, Ohio","start_year":1801}],"slug":"elijah-